The border agression in 1962 was initiated by Nehru's forward basing. Of course the chinese reacted much more aggresively so they increased the stakes, but it is important to note the initiation considering all the 'back stabbing' propaganda.<br>
I don't think china has any designs for India. India is way too populated for any invader to desire land etc...<br>
Of course it is to China's strategic advantage to prevent an immediate resolution to the border dispute because being more powerful at the moment, it is most useful to have some sort of bait or readymade provocation if future situations demand it. So there is nothing unnatural in the lack of resolution to the dispute. If India wants to resolve it, it has to show more strength and shrewdness in politics, rather than assuming the  betrayed friend attitude. For example, it could make some decisive advances in the case of a Taiwan conflict, or could gain concessions prior to a Taiwan conflict, in exchange for a non-agression treaty. Of course China can do the same in case of an Indo-Pak war.<br>
Second there is a massive geographical barrier between the two countries. Bear in mind that inspite of being two of the oldest civilisations which are geographically neighbours, there is virtually NO similarity between the cultures. Modern maps create the illusion of their being Neighbours, but the china immediately across the himalayas is a cast cold desert called the Tibetan plateau, the real china lying almost completely in the east, south east.<br>
Third, the strategies of the two countries to power are vastly different reflecting the difference in culture and race as well.<br>
I would say the average chinese is : more efficient in work, more intelligent in the mechanical sense(if you factor in India's vast Australoid tribal populations.), and more homogenous. Therefore insofar as organizing vast basic industries, mass production, distribution of state resources, and catching up in technology are concerned, the chinese have a clear advantage.<br>
Their political system has the advantage of being free of the crippling weakness of democracy and can act decisively. However in the long run their government system only reinforces the chinese homogeneity.<br>
India has advantages in producing independent intellectual work, in producing dynamic aristocratic individuals, and in maintaining natural strength. This often leads to weakness in the form of corruption and self serving nepotism etc, but it is a consequence of individuals less subjugated to the state. Whether this is good or bad, I will leave you witha  quote from Nietzsche : &quot; The more developed the state the more distant is humanity.&quot; <br>
India has a far freer society, but this is a weakness insofar as it is a clear and indisputable fact of nature that men are inequal and the average man is not to be given freedoms.<br>
However the hierarchical system of India has in it the seeds to regenerate higher culture the world over, in the form of aristocratic culture etc. India also seems to me to have more cultural resilience than China because it has withstood the depradations of western degeneration to a greater extent. But the chinese have greater political resilience. Also the recent globalization of both countries is a threat toboth cultures.<br>
I would say that neither countries at the moment have the inherent agression to have designs for empire or confrontation. Indians have greater agression, and more aristocratic blood which would predispose them to expansionism to a greater degree. But the chinese political system has a greater agressive and unified force, so that the phenomenon of modern china may gain agression over and above the personality disposition of the average chinese.<br>
In the short run I expect the chinese to really  outsrip India as they have already done. India has vast demographic problems and the backward peoples of that land are reproducing much faster, degrading the genetic stock. There is a good chance of the entire country sinking into Biharesque, tribal factionalism and warfare.<br>
The chinese have a sort of dynamism for work, but this dynamism is rarely seen in a spirit of intellectual independence etc. <br>
As long as the current shopkeepers world of global capitalism along with democracy persists, china will have the edge. <br>
However in the long run, I believe India's greater population diversity, with the naturalness of culture has the seeds for generating the individual genius and exceptional men that are the true and original sources of higher civilisation(as in europe and greece in the past.) China may be eliminating permanently its ability to produce great men, by the homogenization that has existed for so long and the politically radical system that enforces one child births(a sort of self castration) and supression of dissent. Thus I think that the burden of releasing the earth from the cultural sewers of the modern Anglo-saxon  civilisations rests with India, and it has the chance to play a greater role in world history than it ever has, at par with Europe or Greece.<br>
-Tamerlane<br>
